Man, that's overkill.  I find that a dictionary is heavy enough to beat myself senseless to escape the frustration.  I've never had to resort to an entire encyclopedia.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
What we do now is try to keep him focused enough to do the regular schoolwork well.  This is a bigger challenge than it might sound, since like a lot of fast-thinkers he's very quick to find the least amount of work necessary to squeak by, and sink to that.  Beyond that, we try to supplement him at home with stuff to keep him engaged.  He's going into middle school this year, and it's an accelerated magnet school so we'll see.  We're cautiously hopeful at this point.<br>
<br>
I figure, when school stops being passive social conditioning and starts being actually harmful to him, we'll pull him out and do something else since we're already homeschooling him.  But until then, I want to mainstream him as much as possible... he's MY kid, and needs all the &quot;mainstream&quot; help he can get...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>My public education story reads like a nightmare.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yours and mine, both.  For various reasons, my parent situation was such that I was not kept engaged or particularly kept track of after about the fifth grade.  I have the same &quot;least amount necessary&quot; disease my son has, and in an environment where nobody was paying attention, I was neither held accountable for my work nor given new roads to explore.<br>
<br>
By the time I got to high school, I'd learned how to blow off work entirely and disappear from school.  I spent the last two years of high school in the library.  Not sure why, I probably should have spent the time more wisely by experimenting with freaky chemicals.  <br>
<br>
About a year after my class graduated (after which I found a job rather than sitting in a library), I went back and got my GED for fun.  That was the only part of school I enjoyed.  They were getting ready to set me up for prep classes, and I said, &quot;No, I just want to take the test.  Here.  Now.&quot;<br>
<br>
The secretary person looked at the clock and said, &quot;Well, we can get you started on the first one, but it's like an eight hour five part test,&quot; or something like that.  So I sat down and took the test.  Less than four hours later, they had a stack of papers all filled out, very few mistakes <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
I still look back and think, &quot;Hell, if that was all I needed to know in high school, they should've just fed it to me and I'd have been done at 15...&quot;<br>
<br>
But it was misery slogging through it.  So long as I'm alive, at least, my child won't have the same experience that way...<br>
